wever, at transformative moments in political history, states turn to faith-based appeals to integrate or fragment international coalitions. Henne highlights Saudi Arabia's 1960s rivalry with Egypt, the United States's post-9/11 leadership in the global war on terrorism, and the Russian Federation's contemporary expansionism both to reveal the presence and power of calls for religious unity and to emphasize the uncertainty and anxiety such appeals can create. Religious Appeals in Power Politics offers a bold corrective to those who consider religion as tangential to military or economic might.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPower (Social sciences)xReligious aspects. 0aReligion and international relations. 0aReligion and politicszRussia. 0aReligion and politicszSaudi Arabia. 0aReligion and politicszUnited States. 4aInternational Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aRussian Christianity, Saudi Arabia, religion and international relations, Pan-Arabism, Al-Qaeda, Islamic State, Mohammad bin Salman.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz978311131925408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023z9783111318677oZDB-23-PLW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501770524?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501770524423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501770524/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell Univer